This pull request makes it possible to push errors to the debugger with an exception that was thrown elsewhere. This would be useful for libraries like GDTask which run user code.

**Example:**

This is a simple runner that queues actions to run on the next frame:

```cs
public partial class MyExampleRunner : Node {
    private readonly Queue<Action> ActionsQueued = [];

    public override void _Process(double delta) {
        while (ActionsQueued.TryDequeue(out Action? action)) {
            try {
                action();
            }
            catch (Exception ex) {
                GD.PushError(ex); // Debugger takes you here
            }
        }
    }
    public void QueueAction(Action action) {
        ActionsQueued.Enqueue(action);
    }
}
```

This is an example that uses `MyExampleRunner`:

```cs
public partial class MyExampleRun : Node {
    public override void _Ready() {
        Callable.From(() => {
            MyExampleRunner myExampleRunner = GetParent().GetNode<MyExampleRunner>("MyExampleRunner");

            myExampleRunner.QueueAction(() => GD.Print(1));
            myExampleRunner.QueueAction(() => GD.Print(2));
            myExampleRunner.QueueAction(() => throw new Exception("test message")); // Debugger should take you here
            myExampleRunner.QueueAction(() => GD.Print(3));
        }).CallDeferred();
    }
}
```

On the `throw new Exception("test message")` line, the ideal behaviour would be for the debugger to take you to the line that throws the exception (commented `Debugger should take you here`). But actually, the debugger takes you to the line that pushes the error (commented `Debugger takes you here`).

Part of implementing my [proposal](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/13875). Repurposing the mesh compression AABB allows it to work for all meshes. Note that this gives the bounds of the current surface rather than the mesh as a whole, but it’s still a win for shader programmers.

  The sign bit of size.x in the shader determines if compression is enabled, which assumes that the AABB size should be positive. This means that to decode the size we do abs(size), which is already encapsulated by AABB_SIZE. It's an implementation detail and not something the user has to think about.

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/e4b69a73-9240-4968-bb31-c26d5c447d4d

I have tested the AABB on each renderer, with compressed and uncompressed meshes, and with MultiMeshInstance3D.

